@Node Require "What do you need"
BKick needs:

Blizzard Turbo Board 1230 II, III or IV, 1260
(maybe BKick will work with another boards from @{"phase 5" Link phase5})

with enabled MapROM
@EndNode


@Node phase5
phase 5 digital products
In der Au 27
D-61440 Oberursel, Germay
@EndNode


@Node Usage
Template:	BKick	KICK,ROM/S,FORCE/S,EXEC/S

BKick let you load a kickstart file into Blizzard Turbo Board's MapROM
memory.  That means that you can easily change a kickstart.

Use @{b}BKick <kickstart filename>@{ub} to load a given kickstart to a
memory.  Kickstart file may be either 256KB or 512KB.  BKick can load
kickstart stored in @{b}DEVS:Kickstarts@{ub} directory, and you don't need
to type the full path.

If you want to change the kickstart back to that you have in ROM, use
@{b}BKick ROM@{ub} on systems V36 and above, or just @{b}BKick@{ub} on
pre-V36 systems.

BKick can't load a kickstart from file on pre-V36 systems.


BKick will refuse loading kickstart, which has the same version number as
that already loaded, until FORCE specified.


EXEC option lets you move exec.library to fast memory to gain system speed.
It also sets Blizzard memory flags to MEMF_LOCAL and MEMF_KICK, so
Recoverable Ram Drives (like RAD:) will work now.  You can move exec also
for ROM kickstart.  Note that EXEC option works only with 512KB kickstarts.
@EndNode


@Node Errors
BKick may quit with the following error messages:

@{b}No Blizzard or Map ROM disabled@{ub}
	You have no Blizzard memory expansion, or you have a model with
	doesn't work with BKick, or you forgot to set MapROM jumper (refer
	to the manual how to do that).

@{b}Kickstart file not found@{ub}	
	The given kickstart file was not found in the current nor
	@{b}DEVS:Kickstarts@{ub} directory.

@{b}Invalid kickstart file@{ub}
	The kickstart file have different size than 256K (262144 bytes) or
	512K (524288 bytes), or BKick failed on reading.

@{b}Not enough memory@{ub}
	There is not enough memory to load kickstart file.

@{b}Kickstart already installed@{ub}	
	The given kickstart version number equals to the version of the
	already loaded one.  If you must load it, use the FORCE.

@{b}Kickstart checksum error@{ub}
	The given kickstart have a wrong checksum.  Probably it is not a
	kickstart file.


Note that BKick returns OK if it fails, and reboots if success.
@EndNode


